<handout>
<title>Worksheet 1.2, Row Reduction and Echelon Forms</title>
    <page>
      <ul marker="">
        <li workspace="2in"> 
          <p>(1) &#160; <em>Written Explanation Exercise.</em> Answer each of the following in one or two sentences.</p>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
              <p>What are some of the differences between echelon form and row reduced echelon form (RREF)? List at least three.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>How can we use row reduction to determine whether an augmented matrix corresponds to a consistent system?</p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </li>

        <li workspace="2in">
          <p>(2) &#160; Which matrices are in RREF? In echelon form?</p>
          <p>
            <m>
              A = \begin{pmatrix}0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \end{pmatrix},\quad
              B = \begin{pmatrix}
              1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2\\
              0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \amp 0\\
              0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1
              \end{pmatrix},\quad
              C = \begin{pmatrix}0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 5 \amp 5 \end{pmatrix}
            </m>
          </p>
          <p><em>Note:</em> Any missing entries above are as printed in the original; interpret dimensions/context as appropriate for echelon/RREF classification.</p>
        </li>

        <li workspace="2in">
          <p>(3) &#160; List all <m>3\times 2</m> matrices in RREF. Use <m>\ast</m> for entries that can be arbitrary.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </page>

    <page>
      <ul marker="">
        <li workspace="1in">
          <p>(4) &#160; Indicate whether the statements are true or false.</p>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
              <p>A linear system whose <m>3\times 5</m> coefficient matrix has three pivotal columns must be consistent.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>The echelon form of a coefficient matrix is unique.</p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </li>

        <li workspace="2in">
          <p>(5) &#160; For any three distinct points in the plane, no two on a vertical line, there is a second‑degree polynomial 
            <m>p(t)=a_{0}+a_{1}t+a_{2}t^{2}</m> that passes through those three points. Construct the polynomial that passes through 
            <m>(1,12)</m>, <m>(2,15)</m>, and <m>(3,16)</m>. That is, solve
          </p>
          <p>
            <md>
              \begin{aligned}
              p(1)\amp=12=a_{0}+a_{1}+a_{2}\\
              p(2)\amp=15=a_{0}+2a_{1}+4a_{2}\\
              p(3)\amp=16=a_{0}+3a_{1}+9a_{2}
              \end{aligned}
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>(The coefficient matrix is an instance of the <em>Vandermonde matrix.</em>)</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </page>
    
</handout>
